node.text:
Over a six-month period, artist and educator @chanelthervil met virtually with young Boston-area artists, facilitating discussions and art-making activities that focused on creating visual patterns to affirm their life experiences and capacity for greatness. Their collaborative project is now on view in our Linde Family Wing for Contemporary Art!

"Patterns of Greatness" marks the 16th year of the Community Arts Initiative, through which the MFA partners with community organizations to introduce young people ages 6 to 12 to the Museum’s collection and the art-making process.

node.title: Community Arts Initiative: Patterns of Greatness

This year marks the 15th year of our Community Arts Initiative, through which we partner with local after-school organizations to introduce kids ages 6 to 12 to the Museum's collection and the art-making process 🎉 

For the 2020 Community Arts Initiative Artist Project, Sarah Pollman (@sarahkpollman) collaborated with young artists to create a large-scale, wall-hung relief sculpture that charts global exchange pathways of the goods, services and ideas of artists.

See their final piece when "Community Arts Initiative: Exchange Codes" opens on November 11—the exhibition is included in general admission!

node.text:
Boston, we can't wait to share "Writing the Future: Basquiat and the #HipHopGeneration" with you 👑 

Earlier this year, we convened musicians, artists, educators, academics, financiers, social workers and creative professionals through our new Table of Voices initiative. At a series of roundtables and gatherings, they discussed Jean-Michel #Basquiat's impact on their lives and work—and his influence in shaping hip-hop culture in our city.

We're deeply grateful for this group's contributions to the exhibition’s interpretation, outreach and programming: Khamari Anderson, Chris Barnes, Kristen Catlin, Shaka Dendy (@shakadendy), Shaumba Dibinga, Rahn Dorsey, Niki DuFauchard, Ed O.G., Lisa Finelli Fallon, Murray Forman, Kerry Foster, Rob (@problak) Gibbs, Daren Graves, Tim Hall (@tv_hall), Leroy Irvin (@bostonlirvin), Stacy Lewis, Oompa (@oompoutloud), Moe Pope (@moepope), REKS (Corey Isiah Christie), DJ Riobamba (@riobamba_dj), Greg Shell, Tyrone Smith, Justin Springer, Rob Stull (@robstull24), Billy Dean Thomas (@billydeanthomas), Kris N. Tyler, Aysha Upchurch (@ayshadances), C Wells and DeJongh Dee Wells.

"Writing the Future" opens to the public on October 18!

node.text: A multi-instrumentalist, @gracegivertz uses her honest lyrics to bring a refreshing sound to folk. In this edition of our Nancy Lee Clark Sound Bites Concert Series, the Boston-based singer-songwriter performs original songs chosen in response to artworks from our exhibition “Women Take the Floor.” Givertz is introduced by Layla Bermeo, Kristin and Roger Servison Associate Curator of American Paintings.

node.text:
Transitioning their works from subway trains and city walls onto canvas, Jean-Michel #Basquiat and his peers fueled new directions in visual art, design and music—giving rise to the now-global popularity of hip-hop and changing pop culture forever.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We've loved celebrating these artists with "Writing the Future: Basquiat and the #HipHopGeneration" 👑 Don't miss your last chance to see the exhibition—this Sunday, July 25 is the final day!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🎬 We're bidding goodbye to "Writing the Future" with a free outdoor screening of "Wild Style," one of the earliest records of hip-hop culture, on our front lawn! Join us, director Charlie Ahearn (@twincharlie) and artist @fab5freddy on Sunday night (link in our bio for event details).⁣⁣
⁣
The exhibition is sponsored by @bankofamerica.⁣
⁣⁣
🖼️: "Hollywood Africans" (1983), Jean-Michel Basquiat, acrylic and oilstick on canvas, on loan from @whitneymuseum⁣⁣
⁣⁣
[Image description: Painting featuring a triple portrait of three men on a yellow background, with words—some crossed out—written all over the canvas]

node.text:
It's bath time for our baby heads! 🧼⁣
⁣
Our @mfaconservation summer interns Mayuli Santiesteban and Pilar Brooks were recently joined by the STEAM Team—one of our @mfateens programs—for the maintenance of "Day" and "Night" (2008), the two large sculptures by Antonio López García that are located on either side of the Fenway entrance.⁣
⁣
🧽 The interns first washed the sculptures to remove soiling and debris, and then worked with the STEAM Team to apply and buff a layer of protective black wax to the surface.⁣ #mfaConservation

In this late-night scene of the then-ubiquitous corner drug store, #EdwardHopper’s New York City is deserted and ominously silent. No people stroll along the sidewalk. No cars crowd the street. The sense of danger lurking in the shadows negates the welcome of the brightly lit window.⁣
⁣
The painting is one of the early masterpieces by the artist, who was born #OnThisDay in 1882 🎂 ⁣
⁣
🖼️: "Drug Store" (1927), oil on canvas ⁣
⁣
[Image description: Painting of a pharmacy on a street corner; the window displays red and green apothecary bottles and a sign that reads, "Prescription Drugs / Ex Lax"]

Ming Smith (@mingsmithphoto) was the only female member of the all-Black Kamoinge Workshop that formed in New York City during the 1960s and 70s. The term "Kamoinge," from the language of the Kenyan Kikuyu people, means “working together”; members of the workshop recorded the vibrant street life of Harlem and the jazz and fashion scenes of the day.⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
📷: "Amen Corner Sisters, New York City, NY" (1976, printed later), photograph, gelatin silver print, on view in "Women Take the Floor"⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
[Image description: Black-and-white photograph of two Black women seated on a bench; they are wearing formal dresses and hats, and one of them holds a fan imprinted with a photograph of two Black girls and puppies]

We hosted a special visitor at the MFA last week—Michael C. Thorpe (@iversonsdurag), whose work will be featured in our upcoming "Fabric of a Nation: American Quilt Stories" exhibition!⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
🧵 The artist toured the Museum with Jennifer Swope, David and Roberta Logie Associate Curator of Textile and Fashion Arts, and was particularly drawn to this piece by Gee's Bend quilter Annie Mae Young, which is on view in "New Light: Encounters and Connections." ⁣⁣⁣

This painting by Edgar #Degas shows his father, who had instilled in his son a love of music, listening attentively to Lorenzo Pagans. The Spanish-born tenor made a reputation performing songs of his native land in Parisian salons of the 1860s. ⁣
⁣
🎂 Degas was born #OnThisDay in 1834—you can see more of his work in our #Impressionism gallery!⁣
⁣
🖼️: "Degas’s Father Listening to Lorenzo Pagans Playing the Guitar" (about 1869–72), oil on canvas ⁣
⁣
[Image description: Painting of a man in a suit singing and playing the guitar; another man sits next to him, his head framed by a sheet of music on a piano behind him]
